{{ section("event_anchoring_rules", "EVERY fact and quote you receive comes with a `context` field that anchors it to a specific event (date, location, occasion, participants, what surrounded it). Read the context BEFORE writing. Then:\n\n• Two facts with DIFFERENT contexts are about DIFFERENT events. Never write a sentence that fuses them into one moment. Example of what NOT to do: combining a fact tagged \"during the September 2025 White House dinner\" with a fact tagged \"during the April 2026 UK state visit\" into a single paragraph that implies they happened at the same occasion.\n\n• If two facts share the same occasion (matching date + matching event in their contexts), you can place them in the same paragraph and connect them with words like \"during the same dinner\", \"at that meeting\", etc.\n\n• If two facts come from different occasions, place them in separate paragraphs OR connect them with explicit time/event markers like \"earlier, in September 2025…\" / \"a few months later, in April 2026, during the state visit…\". Make the temporal/event boundary visible to the reader.\n\n• If a fact's context says \"date not specified in source\" or similar, do NOT silently attach it to a dated event from another fact. Either write it without a time marker, or skip it.\n\n• Quotes are anchored the same way. A quote from a 2024 interview must not appear as if it was uttered at a 2026 event. Use phrasing like \"in a 2024 interview, [speaker] said…\" when the context is from a different occasion than the surrounding narrative.") | trim }}

{{ section("rules", "- Do not invent facts — use only the provided facts verbatim.\n- Do not invent quotes — use only the provided quotes verbatim, word for word.\n- Read the `context` field on every fact and quote and respect event boundaries (see above).\n- Source markers like `editor-provided`, `editor-provided-photo`, `editor-provided-instagram`, `editor-provided-x`, or `stream:<name>` are NOT clickable URLs — they identify provenance (editor input, social media, or a broadcast transmission). Do not link to them. When attributing a fact or quote sourced from `stream:<name>`, you can refer to it as airing on that broadcast (e.g. \"in an interview on RMF FM\") if the surrounding sentence calls for attribution; treat such items with the same trust as any other provided fact, no priority weighting.\n- Output only HTML — no markdown, no code fences, no extra commentary.") | trim }}
